Well,

This is a long-standing debate. There is an excellent book that
illustrates the historical highlights written by Lelia Green called
Communication, Technology and Society.

Green illustrates the two dominant views:

1. Technology is neutral. &quot;Guns don't kill people, people kill people.&quot;
In this view, the objects cannot be blamed for their use, nor the
inventors of the objects.

2. Technology is embedded with an implied use. &quot;Guns are designed to
punch holes in flesh.&quot; In this view, there is an implied purpose
represented in the design of a gun. The presence of the implied use
encourages a particular use.

I used guns because this boils down neatly into the gun control debate.
Those who believe that technology is neutral believe that gun control
is useless. If murderers don't have guns, they will pick up knives or
sharp sticks. It's the people who are responsible.

Those who believe that technology is a shaped by culture and therefore
has an implied intended purpose believe that the ease and simplicity of
a handgun encourage its use to commit murder. They point out that a
murder will not commit as many murders (or perhaps none at all) if
killing were less efficient, or if the act cost the actor more than
simply squeezing a trigger and walking off.

Depending on which view you adopt, your views of gun control are shaped
into a specific perspective.

What I find ironic is that those who believe strongly in gun control
(typically Democrats) do not believe as strongly in controlling nuclear
and biological proliferation. And those who believe gun control is
wrong (typically Republicans) believe in strong WMD control.

But in terms of responsibility, the most interesting case is the
Grokster case being decided by the Supreme Court right now. Unlike the
Napster case, Grokster (the company) has no control over what users do
with its services, meaning the only accountability they have is for
what they have unleashed.

Hollywood, of course, believes that the protocol has only one designed
use: piracy. It wants Grokster held accountable for creating the
protocol.

Those who are arguing for Grokster are saying that if a technology firm
has to consider all the potential uses of a technology before they
produce it or face liability for its misuse, it will create a chill in
the technology sector that we may never recover from. (And of course,
the 1984 Betamax decision has a new relevance, no matter what the
decision is).

Personally, I tend to view how a technology is defined or how it is
used in a society as the responsibility of the society itself. The
inventor or deliverer of a technology can frame a technology's use to a
certain degree, but society can reject this framing or invent its own.

Society often repurposes a technology beyond its original design.
Technologies change and evolve not as a result of the original
innovator, but because of their appeal and creativity of the users.

iPods give birth to Podcasting, possibly changing the future of radio
forever. Does Steve Jobs (or the Apple designers) get the credit/blame?
Well, maybe some. They will claim it. But the users and hackers deserve
most of the credit for these developments.

So, no, I do not think researchers or scientists can be held completely
responsible for the effects and outcomes of the application of their
discoveries and knowledge. Their job is to present alternatives and
potential options for society. It is up to others to take
responsibility for their own use of a given tool or technology.

Should we blame the Chinese because they are generally credited with
the invention of gunpowder for all the gun-related violence in human
history? Or was gun powder irrelevant to the decision to use it to kill
human beings? Or is the responsibility somewhere in between these two
extreme views?

