Dave, appears that several of us must struggle not to assert our
credentials and be more patient with those judging systems and
institutions we have more experience with than they. Good luck on the
last mile of the journey.

The essence of the discussion appears to center around the question of
whether there needs to be some restriction on what a developer can or
can't pursue, and whether this person is accountable for how said
invention is used after it is brought to market.

I think that technology use is socially driven. We create needs and we
determine uses. Designers and scientists may seek solutions to problem
through their work, but ultimately it is he or she that uses the tool
created who must bear the responsibility for that tool's use.

Sam seems to think that there should be some kind of oath or pledge
that those who create new knowledge should take before pursuing an
endeavor.

But I think this is too vague and impractical. Who can say which values
are the best to uphold? Who can say before research is conducted what
they will agree to decide is the best course of action? Who can answer
ethical questions about a new technology before its abilities and
effects are discovered?

And where do we stop? Nuclear physicists? Engineers? Social scientists?
Religious scholars? All of these create new knowledge and new ideas,
much of which has powerful effects on our society.

I am still old school enough that I believe in the marketplace of
ideas. Let knowledge enter the marketplace freely and a society will
decide what is acceptable and what is not through law, commerce and
cultural values (in the form of social pressure).

Scientists should not all be social engineers (except for the social
engineers). Let them concentrate on their fields and let the users
decide how best to use and adopt their output.

